Consistently good is infinitely better than inconsistently perfect.
-
Not my way of encouraging you to half ass it, by the way.
-
My way of...
-
1) Getting you to stop beating yourself up over some holiday pizza or a fat slice of Oreo ice cream cake or cauldron full of Fizzing Whizbees or sack of powdered Sugar Quills or a pan of pumpkin pasties.
-
Ideally, you wouldn’t have the whole lot in one go.
-
But even if you did...it’s not going to make or break your progress.
-
Because, remember, you’re never more than one bite away from being right back on track.
-
And just like no one ever got jacked from one workout or skinny from one salad...no one got fat from one “bad” holiday meal.
-
So relax. Stop beating yourself up for having a treat. Enjoy it. Then get back on plan.
-
2) Encouraging you to stop wasting your time waiting for the “perfect” opportunity.
-
Because it’s never going to come.
-
Ever.
-
You will always be busy. You will always have other things to take care of. You will rarely (if ever) think you’re 100% ready to dive in head first.
-
There will never be a perfect time.
-
You will never be perfectly ready.
-
And the longer you wait for the opportunity to be “perfect,” the longer you delay your chance to make your own magic.
-
And that’s special.
-
So.
-
Stop waiting.
-
Go do it.
-
Now.
-
And don’t forget to have some fun.
-
Love you.
-
PS my next Calorie Cycling for Fat Loss Challenge is open for registration and officially kicks off on Jan 6th. Sign up now at the link in my bio.
-

Some people struggle with self control.
-
They want to lose fat but have difficulty saying “no.”
-
Often times they mentally justify it in saying they’re “flexible dieting.”
-
But flexible dieting doesn’t mean “eat junk and lose fat.” It means “don’t feel guilty for having a treat - but you still have to be wicked consistent to make significant, lasting changes.”
-
For them, practicing self control and saying “no” more often might help them achieve their goal.
-
Other people struggle with food anxiety.
-
They get anxious at the thought of going out to eat at a restaurant because they don’t want to “ruin their progress.”
-
They feel bad for having a slice of cake at their own birthday party.
-
They, logically, know it sounds silly and they often give their friends/family/clients amazing nutrition advice that promotes a more flexible approach...but they struggle with it themselves.
-
For them, saying “yes” more often and having a treat might help them achieve their goals.
-
Progress is not only measured in weight loss or fat loss or measurements or numbers or quantifiable data.
-
Progress is also measured in mental, emotional, and behavioral changes.
-
And, candidly, if you don’t improve your mindset first, any physical changes/improvements are going to be short-lived.
-
Because sustainable results only happen with a sustainable mindset.
-

Some people poo-poo the idea of Mindful Eating as hokey and weird and a waste of time.
-
I disagree.
-
Because, especially for those who struggle with food anxiety, binge eating, or motivation to stay on track...mindful eating can be very helpful.
-
There isn’t a single right or wrong way to practice mindful eating.
-
The premise is to focus on being fully present and “in the moment” (I know it sounds hippy dippy but bear with me) when you eat.
-
No rushing or snacking on the go.
-
When you eat..you full stop, appreciate everything around you, pay attention to how you feel, focus on your food, and remove your mind from your daily stresses to focus on what’s in front of you.
-
To help with that, I made this 7-step checklist (you can save it if you want for later) that you can check off as you make your way through a meal.
-
Again, these aren’t the only points to consider. But I’ve consistently found focusing on these 7 dramatically reduces food anxiety, binges, boredom eating, and improved adherence to your diet.
-
So, with all that said, I hope this helps.
-
Love you.
-

Hey :)
-
Listen.
-
If you’re basing all of your progress on your weight...you’re shitting the bed.
-
I’m not saying your weight isn’t a good tool or indicator of progress.
-
It is, it can be, and I encourage you to both develop a healthy relationship with the scale and use it as a tool.
-
But.
-
The scale is not the end-all-be-all of progress.
-
If your weight stays the same but your pant size goes down...you’re making progress.
-
If your weight stays the same but your belt size goes down...you’re making progress.
-
If your weight stays the same but your measurements go down...you’re making progress.
-
If your weight stays the same but your pictures improve...you’re making progress.
-
The scale is one tool of many.
-
Don’t treat it like the only tool.
-
Because that’s when you set yourself up for failure.
-
Also.
-
Go watch this full video (the link is in my bio).
-
Especially if you struggle with fat loss (even when you’re doing everything right).
-
Love you.
-

Let me make myself abundantly clear.
-
Dolores Umbridge is a fowl, old toad with a violent undertone of flesh eating slugs following her every breath.
-
She also doesn’t believe calories matter.
-
Which brings me to my point.
-
Calories are not all that matter.
-
Of course, your protein intake matters.
-
Of course, your sleep quality matters.
-
Of course, hydration matters.
-
Of course, strength training matters.
-
Of course, food quality matters.
-
No one is saying otherwise.
-
Except, perhaps, Mundungus Fletcher.
-
But he’s a knobbly old fiddle faddle so you shouldn’t pay attention to what he says, anyway.
-
Listen.
-
Just because calories are not all that matter doesn’t mean calories don’t matter at all.
-
They do.
-
A lot.
-
Especially when it comes to your body composition (gaining/losing fat and building muscle).
-
You can have the “cleanest” diet with the “highest quality” foods prepared only with the “finest” ingredients...but if your calories aren’t accounted for...you won’t reach your goals.
-
So.
-
Listen.
-
If you think calories don’t matter, you’re wrong.
-
And if you think calories are all that matter...you’re also wrong.
-
Calories matter. And all calories count.
-
But they aren’t all that matter. And they aren’t the only thing that counts.
-
Love you.
-

If you struggle binge eating please take a few seconds to watch this quick clip (it’s only 51 seconds) and read the caption.
-
The whole thing. No skipping around, ya muggle.
-
First and foremost.
-
It’s important for you to know binge eating is VERY common.
-
It is without question the most common thing people message me about.
-
Everyone from famous models and fitness influencers to people struggling with obesity, hypothyroidism and everyone in between.
-
But.
-
Very few people are publicly open about it.
-
Which is why most people are ashamed of themselves for doing it and don’t tell anyone about it. So they keep quiet.
-
Which makes them feel even more alone and isolated and ashamed. Which leads them to binge more.
-
And so the cycle continues.
-
Listen.
-
1️⃣If you binge eat you are not alone. At all. Mannnny are struggling with you. Please know that.
-
2️⃣I strongly encourage you to speak with a licensed therapist either in-person or on the phone. They can help you with this.
-
3️⃣The first thing you need to do is stop trying to eliminate all of the foods you’ve been told are “bad.” The more you think they’re off limits the more likely you are to binge.
-
4️⃣Keep in mind, struggling with bingeing and struggling with cravings are two entirely separate topics. To reduce cravings you likely will benefit from removing certain foods from your diet for a brief period of time. But before you start trying to reduce cravings you first need to develop a healthy relationship with food. And that begins with understanding there is no such thing as a good or bad food.
-
Any questions?
-
Text me. Seriously.
-
+1 (617) 249-7381
-
If I don’t respond I promise I’m not ignoring you. I just get a lot of text messages (thousands) and it’s impossible to answer everyone. But I do try my best.
-
Love you.
-
#bingeeating #bingeeatingrecovery #bed #ed #edrecovery #eatingdisorderrecovery #fitness #fitspo #health #healthydiet #mentalhealth

To all the angry goblins, dementors, death eaters, and flesh eating slugs who didn’t take the time to watch the video or read the caption...
-
I’m NOT saying anything bad about vegans or a plant-based lifestyle.
-
I fully support however you decide to eat.
-
Because, candidly, I don’t give a fuck whether you’re vegan or paleo or keto or do intermittent fasting or weight watchers or south beach or Voldemort’s Death Inducing Detox.
-
Do what works for you.
-
That said...
-
I have a problem with deliberately deceiving people.
-
And there’s a meme circulating throughout the plant-based community saying broccoli has more protein than beef.
-
Specifically, it says 100 calories of broccoli has more protein than 100 calories of beef.
-
First...no.
-
That’s false. Don’t believe me? Google it. It’s really not that hard of a myth to debunk.
-
Second, even if it were true (it isn’t) 100 calories of broccoli is a fully grown mountain troll sized portion. It’s, literally, the size of my face. (Watch the video and you’ll see).
-
Whereas 100 calories of beef can fit in my palm.
-
So if you want to eat a metric fuck ton of broccoli to get your protein...cool. You do you. Your farts will smell worse than Hagrid’s asshole but maybe you’re into that sorta thing, in which case, god bless.
-
That said...
-
Don’t lie about how much protein is in certain foods in an attempt trick people into eating the way you believe to be superior.
-
Be honest. Give accurate information.
-
And let people eat way the way they choose to eat.
-
Odds are...the more open and honest you are, the more receptive they’ll be to your way of thinking.
-
Anyway.
-
Love you.
-
#vegan #veganfood #veganrecipes #veganbreakfast #veganweightloss #veganfoodshare #mythology #myth #foodporn #food #foodgasm

Here’s what I’ve got for the week.
-
1️⃣ Each day begins with a handwritten bullet pointed list of 3-5 things I will accomplish that day. I could write more but I only write what I guarantee I will complete.
-
2️⃣ Complaining is poison. The more you complain the more you blind yourself from seeing all of the good in your life.
-
3️⃣ Optimism is a choice. Keep in mind, optimism does not equate to happiness. Optimism is simply choosing to see the positive options you have moving forward (opposed to pessimism which is choosing to see the potential negative options).
-
4️⃣ Be kind to everyone. Kindness is always a strength, never a weakness.
-
5️⃣ Pandering helps no one. Including you. Always be kind, yes. But kindness at the expense of honesty isn’t really kindness at all. Don’t pander. Be honest.
-
6️⃣ Make the decision that will make you proud at the end of the day. Not the decision that makes you more comfortable in the moment.
-
7️⃣ Eat at least one big ass salad every day. Don’t overcomplicate this. It’s a big ass bowl of veggies. That’s it.

8️⃣ Eat protein at every meal. Self explanatory.

What’s your plan for the week?

Love you.

[Please take 30sec to read this whole caption. It would mean everything to me].
.
The question isn’t whether or not you’ll stay motivated.
.
You won’t.
.
Not because you don’t want to.
.
But because it’s impossible to stay motivated for anything (regardless of how much you want it).
.
In the same way it’s unrealistic to expect to be happy all day, every day...it’s equally unrealistic to expect to be motivated all day, every day.
.
Motivation is a feeling.
.
An emotion.
.
The more you search for it and try to find it hiding in unsuspecting places...the more it will evade you.
.
You might have moments in which you think you finally trapped it.
.
But just like trapping water in your cupped hands...motivation will slip between the cracks in your fingers until, once again, your hands are empty.
.
The question isn’t whether or not you’ll stay motivated.
.
The question is whether or not you’ll do what you say you want to do regardless of whether or not you’re motivated.
.
That’s not a feeling or emotion.
.
That’s your word.
.
Your truth.
.
Your honesty.
.
Your bond.
.
You will not stay forever motivated to do everything you want.
.
None of us will.
.
But the difference between those who succeed and those who don’t lies in who is willing to hold up their end of the bargain...
.
Who is willing to make the decision...
.
Who is willing to do what is right rather than what is easy...
.
Who is willing to make the harder decision that will make you proud rather than the easier decision that will make you comfortable.
.
The question isn’t whether or not you’ll stay motivated.
.
You won’t.
.
So stop looking for motivation.
.
Start asking yourself if you’re ready to commit to doing what you say you want to do regardless of whether or not you’re motivated.
.
Because when you can truthfully agree to doing that...in that moment you will start succeeding far beyond your wildest dreams.
.
Love you.

I used to say, “you can’t outrun your fork.”
-
I was wrong.
-
You can absolutely do enough cardio to create a calorie deficit and lose fat without paying much attention to your nutrition.
-
But.
-
1️⃣If you’re eating like an asshole and throttling a mega fuck ton of calories down your face hole every meal...you’re gonna have to do an outrageous amount of cardio.
-
Not 30 minutes on the elliptical.
-
Hours.
-
Hours upon hours upon hours of mind-numbing cardio to burn as many calories as possible.
-
Which, between you and me, sounds worse than getting repeatedly punched in the penis by a herd of Hippogriffs.
-
2️⃣Which makes it outrageously difficult to sustain long-term.
-
3️⃣Not to mention, it creates a terrible mental & emotional relationship with food & exercise. Because you’re essentially using exercise as a punishment to try and “undo” all the “damage” you did by eating too much.
-
And if you’re using exercise as a punishment and viewing eating too much as “doing damage,” you’re about to have a hellishly awful fitness experience.
-
4️⃣And if you’re spending all that time doing endless amounts of cardio, you probably won’t have much time or energy to strength train.
-
And while some cardio is wicked important and tremendously beneficial for many reasons, so is lifting heavy weights. And doing some of both is better than either alone.
-
So.
-
Moral of the story?
-
1) Don’t use cardio as your primary means of creating a calorie deficit. Nutrition is king for fat loss.
-
2) Don’t put yourself in a situation that puts you in danger of getting repeatedly punched in the dongle by a herd of Hippogriffs.
-
Love you.

Have you ever gone out to dinner, ate enough chips and guac to feed a family of fully grown mountain trolls, then get super worried because you thought you might’ve fucked up your progress?
-
Or.
-
Have you ever been sick or injured or traveling and had to skip a workout or two or three or a whole week? And did you feel bad or guilty or nervous you might’ve fucked up your progress?
-
Listen.
-
I want to tell you something but I don’t want you skimming it bc it’s wicked important so, please, listen.
-
You can’t fuck this up.
-
I’m gonna say it again. Keep reading. Don’t skim.
-
You. Can’t. Fuck. This. Up.
-
I don’t care if you blew past your calories by 3,000 extra.
-
You didn’t fuck up.
-
I don’t care if you missed one workout or two workouts or a month of workouts.
-
You didn’t fuck up.
-
I don’t care if you had an entire box of Cinnamon Toast Crunch, 6 chocolate frogs, 4 pints of butter beer and a trolley full of pumpkin pasties.
-
You didn’t fuck up.
-
Because here’s the magic of it all.
-
The only way to fuck up is if you stop altogether. If you give up. Quit. Say you’re done.
-
Otherwise, you can’t fuck up.
-
It’s impossible.
-
Because as long as you get right back on track you’re going to keep making progress.
-
Most people use, “I fucked up” as an excuse to keep fucking up. To stay off track. To not put in more effort.
-
But that’s codswallop. And as of this moment it’s not a valid excuse.
-
Because you can’t fuck up.
-
As long as you get right back on track, you’re good.
-
This fitness thing?
-
It’s supposed to be fun. It’s supposed to make you happy and smile and confident and proud.
-
It’s not a competition.
-
There is no day or time or hour at which you need to arrive to achieve your goals. There is no rush. You’re playing the long game here. It’s for life, not 7 or 21 or 30 days.
-
This is forever.
-
And when you’re playing forever, you can’t fuck up. Just get right back on track.
-
Love you.

If you struggle with flexible dieting and aren’t sure how to be more moderate with your nutrition (rather than being “all in” or “all out”), you might be doing what many people do in conflating “living in the moment” with “do whatever you want.”
-
Living “presently” and “in the moment” is obviously important and I’m in no way an expert on how to do it.
-
But.
-
Living in the moment isn’t a valid justification for doing whatever you want just because you feel like it.
-
Part of becoming a flexible dieter is learning how to enjoy your favorite foods in moderation without feeling guilty or ashamed or worried you ruined all your progress.
-
Most people focus on the “enjoying your favorite foods” part and neglect the “in moderation” bit.
-
And if that’s you, try thinking about which decision will make you the most proud of yourself.
-
Maybe enjoying the slice of pizza without guilt will make you the most proud because you couldn’t do that before.
-
Or maybe saying no to the pizza because you’re doing your best to hit your calories and you’ve historically struggled with that will make you more proud.
-
There’s no right or wrong.
-
It’s very much dependent on you and what you need as an individual.
-
But be honest with yourself.
-
Ask yourself if you’re doing what you want just because you want to.
-
Or are you doing what you want and living presently in a way that will also make you proud.
-
The option that will make you the most proud is always the right answer.
-
Love you.
